Recognize the condition⁉️ Marfan syndrome - inherited connective tissue disorder that most commonly affects the heart, eyes, blood vessels and skeleton. Marfan syndrome patients are usually tall/thin with unusually long arms, legs, fingers and toes and hypermobile joints. The whole experience was completely surreal. Having multiple rare chronic illnesses and studying biochemistry often means you’ll have professors and chemists bluntly discuss the nitty gritty details of your conditions without any filter, talking about how much money they make and that they utilize “cheaper” alternatives that the shorten a patient’s life but keeps them living just enough to be considered a “cure”. By the researcher standard in the U.S. & FDA a cure is any medication that extends a person’s life ONLY 4 years or more. So a pill that is a death sentence in more than 4 years is still what they call a cure. I don’t blame scientists of course, I am one myself. It was just something I never expected and traumatized from in the moment.  #awareness #chronicillness #chronicillnessawareness #chronicillnesswarrior #jia #biochemistry #disability #disabled #disabledscientist #rheumatoidarthritis #ra #neutropenia #neutropeniaawareness #netropenic

#duet with @Noah and Lori #CouplesTikTok        I’m going to be vulnerable for a moment.  I have been in a relationship where the other person could care less what I had to say. The relationship was all about what I could provide for them. No matter how hard I tried, I couldn’t get them interested in me.  But I ignored those signs and continued to try anyway. I wouldn’t recommend that to anyone. It doesn’t end well and the recovery from all those small moments showing you they don’t care, it takes a really long time to heal from. It impacts your self-worth and what you expect from others.  There are so many signs that someone is in a relationship for what they get out of being in that relationship. And not for genuine interest in their partner.  One thing I have found working with couples is when I ask “what drew you to your partner in the first place?” If they list out how that person made them feel, like “oh they were fun and showed a lot of interest in me, and would always come to all my events and made me feel wanted,” it’s usually a sign of a more transactional relationship. When the partner lists out qualities they admire in the other person like “oh they are so smart, and kind, and warm, and funny,” you can tell there is a true appreciation and recognition of who their partner is as a person. If you liked that popular book, try THIS book The Selection by Kierra Cass -> The Jewel by Amy Ewing I read this book a few years back. It was one of the first serieses that excited me after the downfall of the dystopian era. (The Hunger Games, Divergent, The Selection, etc.) I am a huge dystopian fan, and if you’re looking for a wonderful way to relive this phase, please pick up this series.  The Invisible Life of Addie Larue by V.E. Schwab -> How to Stop Time by Matt Haig This book is written by the author of the booktok book The Midnight Library, another one of my favorites. This book is impeccably written and colorfully emotional, flashing from past to present as we watch our main character fall into a painful love in which he cannot hold on to. If He Had Been With Me by Laura Nowlin -> The Light We Lost by Jill Santopolo These two books have one major element in common: sadness. I found this book more relatable than I wanted to, reading it while going through my first and only real breakup. The characters in this book feel so real and fall into a love that is innocent and complicated and natural and full of chemistry. I have yet to find a book that makes me feel the way this one did. The love story in this book is pungent and sharp and will leave you feeling equally as hopeful and hopeless. Archer's Voice by Mia Sheridan -> Only Love Can Hurt Like This by Paige Toon This book is a small town romance done well. It deviates from the general predictions we see constantly within the trope, but fulfills us in the areas we rely on. This book not only offers a beautiful romance, but a blossoming familial story. Cat Fact of the Day: Just saw the prequel! Not too long ago, I rewatched the entire series. One noticable change was Primrose’s cat — in the first movie, Buttercup is portrayed by a tuxedo cat. The cat did not reflect the book’s description. Katniss describes Buttercup as hideous, muddy-yellow cat. Nina Jacobson, one of the producers, was very upset about this. In an interview, she lamented: “I don't know how that happened because somehow or another, I missed the casting of that cat. I am very present and active as a producer, but somehow I must not have been in the office that day or I must have been in another meeting”  Jacobson also agonized over the casting decision: “I get to set the day that we're shooting, and the cat just shows up, and it's a big black-and-white cat. And I was like, 'What's that in doing here? That's not Buttercup!”  She couldn’t get a new cat until the next movie. Francis Lawrence reportedly had requests from Nina Jacobson and Suzanne Collins to recast the cat. Buttercup is played by an orange Maine Coon tabby in Catching Fire and both of the Mockingjays movies #catsoftiktok #cats #cattok #catfacts #funfacts #meow #cutecat #funfact #learnontiktok #thehungergames #balladofsongbirdsandsnakes #orangecat #meow #catperson #catlady #catperson

If you liked that popular book, try THIS book The Selection by Kierra Cass -> The Jewel by Amy Ewing I read this book a few years back. It was one of the first serieses that excited me after the downfall of the dystopian era. (The Hunger Games, Divergent, The Selection, etc.) I am a huge dystopian fan, and if you’re looking for a wonderful way to relive this phase, please pick up this series.  The Invisible Life of Addie Larue by V.E. Schwab -> How to Stop Time by Matt Haig This book is written by the author of the booktok book The Midnight Library, another one of my favorites. This book is impeccably written and colorfully emotional, flashing from past to present as we watch our main character fall into a painful love in which he cannot hold on to. If He Had Been With Me by Laura Nowlin -> The Light We Lost by Jill Santopolo These two books have one major element in common: sadness. I found this book more relatable than I wanted to, reading it while going through my first and only real breakup. The characters in this book feel so real and fall into a love that is innocent and complicated and natural and full of chemistry. I have yet to find a book that makes me feel the way this one did. The love story in this book is pungent and sharp and will leave you feeling equally as hopeful and hopeless. Archer's Voice by Mia Sheridan -> Only Love Can Hurt Like This by Paige Toon This book is a small town romance done well. It deviates from the general predictions we see constantly within the trope, but fulfills us in the areas we rely on. This book not only offers a beautiful romance, but a blossoming familial story. The details of Michaelangelo #michaelangelo #statueofdavid #ww2

The David statue is a famous sculpture created by the Italian artist Michelangelo. It depicts the Biblical hero David, who is shown standing in a pose of contemplation and readiness for battle. The statue was commissioned by the government of Florence, Italy and took Michelangelo three years to complete. When it was unveiled in 1504, the David statue was hailed as a masterpiece and became a symbol of the Republic of Florence. The statue is carved from a single block of marble and stands 17 feet tall. It is considered one of the greatest works of art in history and is renowned for its impressive physicality and Michelangelo's skill in depicting the human form. The David statue is currently on display at the Galleria dell'Accademia in Florence, Italy.

For my fellow North Americans - it’s okay to have ties to other countries. Your parents, grandparents, whatever, might be from another country, I know. That plays into American culture and is important. Immigrants are important. However, it’s also okay to have a national identity. Support land back, yes, 100%, but you don’t have to erase your cultural identity or feel ashamed of being North American. It doesn’t make you a bad person or overly nationalistic to like where you’re from and deconstruct colonialism. Listen to Harry Belafonte. Appreciate your culture. You have culture. Your accent is beautiful. You are North American. You’re not European. You’re from a beautiful continent, and it isn’t the “lite” version of anywhere else. When Edward Walpole fell ill and passed away his younger brother Robert Walpole Jr moved home to manage the family estate, this led him to later go into politics eventually joining the British Parliament. It was when he was working for Parliament he met his wife. Eventually they had a son named Horace Walope. Three years after the birth of Horace, Robert was chosen to be britians first prime minister. This led to much wealth to the Walpole family. This wealth allowed Horace to pursue an education in politics at prestigous universities like Eton and Cambridge. However he felt his political career would always be overshadowed by his father’s. This instilled him with a pessimistic atitude snd caused him to leave politics alltogether. He then switched to a career in literature. This culminated in him writing what is often hailed as the first horror novel, “The Castle of Ortranto”. This novel birthed the horror genre that only grew more in the 19th century with novels like “Frankenstine”, “Dracula”, and the tales of Edgar Allen Poe. In the 20th century many of these classic tales as well as modern ones from authors like Stephen King began gettinng adapted into film, even further popularizing the genre. This popularization led to the creation of horror video games in the 1980s which also grew in popularity overtime. This led to Scott Cawthon developing the Five Nights At Freddy’s series. Due to attention from the internet it became a massive success leading into a very popular franchise being created. #stitch with @Cesca Liu In facial plastic surgery, the concept of vertical fifths plays a crucial role in achieving facial harmony and balance. Vertical fifths refer to the division of the face into five equal parts vertically, with each part representing a specific facial feature. Surgeons use this aesthetic guideline to assess and plan procedures that enhance facial proportions. By understanding how vertical fifths relate to the eyes, nose, mouth, chin and ears, we can tailor our surgical and non-surgical techniques (like filler) to create a more harmonious and natural facial appearance, ensuring that no one feature dominates the face, ultimately leading to a pleasing and balanced result for our patients.  It’s also a way to play around with makeup and contouring to enhance certain facial features! However, it’s important to understand that these are just guidelines, and should never be used as a rigid standard of beauty or as a source of insecurity. #stitch with @Cesca Liu In facial plastic surgery, the concept of vertical fifths plays a crucial role in achieving facial harmony and balance. Vertical fifths refer to the division of the face into five equal parts vertically, with each part representing a specific facial feature. Surgeons use this aesthetic guideline to assess and plan procedures that enhance facial proportions. By understanding how vertical fifths relate to the eyes, nose, mouth, chin and ears, we can tailor our surgical and non-surgical techniques (like filler) to create a more harmonious and natural facial appearance, ensuring that no one feature dominates the face, ultimately leading to a pleasing and balanced result for our patients.  It’s also a way to play around with makeup and contouring to enhance certain facial features! However, it’s important to understand that these are just guidelines, and should never be used as a rigid standard of beauty or as a source of insecurity. Every person's face is unique and beautiful in its own way, and beauty cannot be reduced to a specific set of measurements or proportions. #drkieutips #horizontalthirds #333333filter  #verticalfifths #2020202020 #2020202020filter #facialharmony #facialbalancing

Case study 70 - Prion disease AKA mad cow disease or Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) @ladyspinedoc  Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) is a transmissible spongiform encephalopathy that results in rapidly progressive dementia and death usually within a year from onset. The vast majority are sporadic, but familial and acquired forms are occasionally encountered. Prion diseases occur when normal prion protein, found on the surface of many cells, becomes abnormal and clump in the brain, causing brain damage. This abnormal accumulation of protein in the brain can cause memory impairment, personality changes, and difficulties with movement. Experts still don't know a lot about prion diseases, but unfortunately, these disorders are generally fatal. #neurosurgery #casestudy #sundaycasestudy  #ladyspinedoc #healthcareworker #hospital #surgery #neurosurgeon #medicalschool #medstudent #medicalstudent #nursing #pastudent #paschool #nursingschool  #dementia #brain #mri #ataxia #myoclonus  #prion #priondisease #cjd #CreutzfeldtJakobdisease #madcow #madcowdisease #kuru

Baby approved Mofongo bites! I’m trying to introduce liam to as many different foods possible and let’s not forget he’s half Puerto Rican so you know this was on the menu lol. I did top them off with some cheese and put them back in the oven for the cheese to melt a little but I got side tracked and almost burnt this whole batch so don’t do that lol.  Ps: I missed him grabbing the food because his dad is a goofball!  All you need: 1/2 lb ground beef 2 sweet plantains Seasoning of your choice, I used garlic,onion powder, cumin, pepper, oregano, roasted red bell peppers and cilantro Cut sweet plantain into small slices and steam them for about 5 minutes or until soft. Using a grinder or fork mash plantains and then place them in a mini muffin pan (spray with cooking oil). Shape them into cup forms and place them in the oven at 350 degrees for 10-15 minutes.  For the ground beef cook until fully brown then drain excess grease. Add your seasoning and finish cooking.  When sweet plantains are done, add ground beef on top plus any toppings you desire. You can pick the whole flower at a go and seperate the stamens later or you can just pick the stamens out of the flower. Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) is a group of inherited connective tissue disorders characterized by joint hypermobility, stretchy skin, easy bruising, and increased scarring. … Symptoms vary by type, and while there’s no cure, treatment focuses on managing symptoms. … Early diagnosis improves management and quality of life. … These are the most common types … 	1.	Hypermobile EDS (hEDS): This is the most common type, characterized by generalized joint hypermobility, often accompanied by chronic pain. Genetic markers are not yet identified, and diagnosis is clinical. 	2.	Classical EDS (cEDS): Features include skin hyperextensibility, easy bruising, and wider joint hypermobility. Atrophic scars, which are thin and sunken, are also common. 	3.	Vascular EDS (vEDS): The most severe form, it carries risks of arterial, intestinal, and uterine complications or ruptures. Skin may appear translucent, showing underlying veins. … To learn more follow @Whealth who both have EDS! … #EhlersDanlosSyndrome #EDS #hEDS #ZebraStrong #EDSAwareness #edswarrior

6 Epic Things to on on your first trip to Boston:  📌Save this post for your future travel plan Boston should be on your radar!! There was so much history and beautiful architecture. If you can’t make it to England from the US  anytime soon, consider a trip to Boston, Ma.  Boston is a great destination for a holiday weekend or extended weekend getaway. You could get away with only using 1-2 days of PTO 🇺🇸 Walk the Freedom Trail- This is honeslty one of the best things to do in Boston. It’s easy to personalize it to your travel plans. I recommend a walking tour, if your short on time!  🫖 Boston Tea Party Ships and Museums- Yes , this is touristy, BUT it was SO well done and a necessity for your first time in Boston. It’s interactive, you get to yell, hiss, and boo, so kids would love this. 🌳Boston Common and Boston Public Garden- Boston Public Gardens was seriously dreamy! Located right across the street, Boston Common begins the Freedom Trail.  🦞 Eat a Lobster Roll- I had a lobster budget, ate it the whole time, and then blew the budget . Worth it 😬 🏡 Explore Beacon Hill- This area is what you think of when you here Boston! Acorn Street is so cute but don’t annoy the locals.  🏟️Catch a game at Fenway Park- If you like sports, Fenway was such a good experience even though my husband was clearly rooting for the other team. Pablo Picasso draws a face. Filmed in France, 1956  Pablo Picasso, born in 1881 in Málaga, Spain, was a prolific and influential artist whose career spanned most of the 20th century. From a young age, his artistic talent was evident, and he received early training from his father, an art teacher. Picasso's artistic evolution can be divided into distinct periods. In his early career, he went through what is known as the "Blue Period," where his art featured somber and melancholic themes, often depicting poverty and despair. This was followed by the "Rose Period," characterized by warmer, more optimistic colors and depictions of circus performers and harlequins. Around 1907, Picasso co-founded the Cubist movement with Georges Braque, which revolutionized art by emphasizing abstract and fragmented forms. This marked a significant departure from traditional representation.  During his career, Picasso also ventured into Surrealism, collaborating with artists like Salvador Dalí. This period saw the exploration of dreamlike and fantastical themes in his work. One of Picasso's most famous works is "Guernica," created as a response to the Spanish Civil War This nassive mural-sized painting serves as a powerful antiowar statement, showcasing his ability to convey deep emotions through his art. Throughout his life, Picasso continued to experiment with various mediums, including ceramics and sculpture. His artistic legacy is immeasurable, as his ability to innovate and inspire other artists had a profound and lasting impact on the art world.  Today, his works are celebrated and displayed in museums around the world, including the Picasso Museum in Barcelona and the Picasso Museum in Paris. Pablo Picasso's journey as an artist remains a testament to his relentless creativity and his enduring influence on the course of modern art.  #pablopicasso #pablopic #artist #artistsoftiktok #artwork #classicart #history #funfacts #art #arttok #artchallenge #artober
